So here=E2=80=99s a trade.
=09You open two accounts on a commodity futures exchange, Account A and Acc=
ount B.=09Using Account A, you offer to sell 10,000 tons of nickel futures =
at a price of $30,000 per ton ($300 million total notional amount).=09Using=
 Account B, you bid to buy 10,000=C2=A0tons of nickel futures at a price of=
=C2=A0$30,000 per ton.=09Nobody else happens to be trading, so your orders =
cross with each other: Account B buys 10,000=C2=A0futures from Account A.=
=09You have to post some collateral in each account, but it=E2=80=99s a fra=
ction of the total notional amount. Say it=E2=80=99s $30 million in Account=
 A and $30 million in Account B, $60 million total.=09You also go around to=
 all the nickel producers and buy up all the nickel they=E2=80=99re produci=
ng. Say you spend $130 million to buy all their nickel just to hoard it for=
 yourself.=09As a result, the price of nickel doubles, to $60,000 per ton.=
=09Now Account B has $300 million of profits, though Account A has $300 mil=
lion of losses.=09Using Account B, you withdraw your $300 million of profit=
s from the futures exchange and bury it in your backyard.=09Simultaneously,=
 the futures exchange issues a margin call to Account A, asking it for $300=
 million more collateral to cover its losses, but that call goes straight t=
o voicemail. Your account is in default, but you opened Account A under a f=
ake name and they never get the money back from you.=09Net, you have put in=
 $190 million ($60 million of futures margin, $130 million to buy up a lot =
of physical nickel) and taken out $300 million, for a $110 million profit.

What is wrong with this trade? I think that there are three general=C2=A0cl=
asses=C2=A0of answer.
One sort of answer is along the lines of: =E2=80=9CThis trade wouldn=E2=80=
=99t work.=E2=80=9D In fact, this trade wouldn=E2=80=99t work. Basically ev=
ery step that I laid out above is superficially plausible, but the actual m=
echanics of nickel markets would prevent you from doing these things. Among=
 other problems, you=E2=80=99d open your futures accounts through brokers, =
who would do know-your-customer checks and get your real name and phone num=
ber, so you couldn=E2=80=99t walk away from Account A. Also the exchange wo=
uldn=E2=80=99t let you trade with yourself. Also there would be a lot of ot=
her people trading on the exchange, so even if the rules allowed you to tra=
de with yourself, the odds of that happening would be low. Also you probabl=
y couldn=E2=80=99t push up the price of nickel all that much by just spendi=
ng $130 million: Nickel is abundant and useful and so hard to corner; you w=
ould need to spend a ton of money relative to the amount you could make on =
the futures exchange.
  [1]
=C2=A0Also if you somehow did manage to double the price of nickel quickly,=
 the exchange might   shut down trading due to =E2=80=9Cthe absence of rati=
onal market forces capable of explaining these developments,=E2=80=9D so yo=
u couldn=E2=80=99t get your money out.=C2=A0The basic idea here is that nic=
kel is a real thing with a real market, and you can=E2=80=99t just push it =
around to do this abstract manipulation. Other people will be doing stuff w=
ith nickel, and your elegant little manipulation will break down when it co=
mes into contact with the real world.
Another sort of answer would be: =E2=80=9CThis trade is illegal.=E2=80=9D I=
t is illegal because it is=C2=A0market manipulation, trading that is =E2=80=
=9Cspecifically intended to create or effect a price or price trend that do=
es not reflect legitimate forces of supply and demand.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0You ha=
ve effectively stolen $300 million from the futures exchange with your unec=
onomic trading, and if you do this trade in large enough size you might ban=
krupt the exchange and=C2=A0cause its other customers to lose money. Other =
people are counting on the nickel exchange to work in a sensible and econom=
ically rational way, and you are treating it as a dumb game. This is bad fo=
r the other users of the futures market, and so it is properly illegal.
A third sort of answer would be: =E2=80=9CThis trade is bad for the world.=
=E2=80=9D It is bad in part=C2=A0because it is market manipulation, stealin=
g from other exchange users, but that=E2=80=99s not the only reason. Nickel=
 is a real thing that real people use in real-world applications, and your =
dumb manipulation requires you to corner the market and push up prices. Peo=
ple can=E2=80=99t make batteries=C2=A0or bathroom fixtures because you are =
doing financial shenanigans. Even if the exchange and its other customers d=
idn=E2=80=99t care =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if everyone trading nickel futures t=
hought =E2=80=9Cwe are playing a dumb game and sometimes we will lose to sm=
arter players=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0this would still be bad, because the =
nickel market has ramifications in the real world.
But let us change the facts slightly. Instead of nickel, let=E2=80=99s do t=
his trade in crypto, on a decentralized finance exchange, and let=E2=80=99s=
 trade the exchange=E2=80=99s own crypto token. We=E2=80=99ll go on Mango M=
arkets, a DeFi trading platform, and trade futures on Mango=E2=80=99s own M=
NGO token. Here we can, sort of, solve all of these objections:
=09The market might be constructed poorly enough that you could actually ge=
t away with doing this. It might let you open accounts without any know-you=
r-customer checks or any recourse to you, it might let you withdraw money i=
nstantly against irrational price moves, it might be illiquid enough that y=
ou could trade with yourself and push up prices dramatically without spendi=
ng much money.=09=E2=80=9CEhh it=E2=80=99s on the blockchain, decentralized=
 finance, no laws apply,=E2=80=9D you might say to yourself. Not legal advi=
ce! We will come back to this one!=09Absolutely no one makes any real-world=
 use of MNGO tokens whatsoever; nobody is deprived of batteries or bathroom=
 fixtures because you briefly cornered some token market.

I don=E2=80=99t want to endorse these arguments, but one could. You might s=
ay: Look, trading MNGO tokens absolutely=C2=A0is, only, a dumb game. It has=
 no consequences in the real world, and also no constraints=C2=A0from=C2=A0=
the real world. Mango=E2=80=99s own rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0the code that dete=
rmines how you set up an account on Mango, how you trade futures, how much =
money you can take out, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0are the only rules that apply t=
o this game, and if those rules allow you to do this thing then you can do =
it. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s market manipulation,=E2=80=9D someone might obj=
ect, but you will reply that that is an irrelevancy, a false analogy to oth=
er markets. This market is just a game, and the rules of this game are just=
 what is encoded in the market=E2=80=99s protocols; =E2=80=9Cmarket manipul=
ation=E2=80=9D is a concept that comes from different markets with other ec=
onomic=C2=A0purposes. Cornering the nickel market is bad, for people who ne=
ed nickel for their kitchens; cornering the MNGO market is morally and econ=
omically neutral.
One problem with this line of thinking is that =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s =
still market manipulation? Like, if you do this, then Mango and its other c=
ustomers=C2=A0will=C2=A0lose money, and you will be taking it from them, an=
d they will feel aggrieved. Many of the reasons that market manipulation is=
 bad in the real world =E2=80=94=C2=A0it feels unfair, it undermines confid=
ence in markets, it takes advantage of smaller less sophisticated traders =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0also apply here.
Another problem with this line of thinking is that, if you=C2=A0like=C2=A0d=
ecentralized finance, if you think it has the potential to build a good alt=
ernative financial system, then this attitude =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthis =
is all a dumb game with no outside rules, and you win the game by tricking =
everyone else=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems bad. Hard to build the financia=
l system of the future on that basis.
A third problem with this line of thinking is that federal prosecutors disa=
gree! They are definitely going to think it=E2=80=99s market manipulation, =
and they=C2=A0  will try to put you in jail:

A cryptocurrency trader accused of rigging the Mango Markets exchange and a=
ttempting to steal $110 million was arrested in Puerto Rico and charged wit=
h fraud by prosecutors in New York.
Avraham Eisenberg allegedly used two Mango Markets accounts he controlled t=
o manipulate the price of Mango perpetual swaps, which are futures that all=
ow traders to keep positions open. All he needed was 20 minutes to push up =
the price of the swaps by 1,300%, according to a criminal complaint unseale=
d [last] Tuesday.
Eisenberg used his swaps, which had increased in value, to borrow, then wit=
hdraw, about $110 million worth of various cryptocurrencies which came from=
 the deposits of other investors on the exchange, according to the complain=
t.
=E2=80=9CDue to Eisenberg=E2=80=99s withdrawals, other investors with depos=
its on Mango Markets lost much, or all, of those deposits,=E2=80=9D the com=
plaint says.
Eisenberg later agreed to return $67 million to Mango, according to the com=
plaint.

We talked about this trade   back in October, and it is schematically what =
I laid out above: Eisenberg sold himself a huge quantity of perpetual MNGO =
futures in the thin Mango futures market, bought a bunch of MNGO in the spo=
t market to manipulate the price up, and then withdrew a bunch of money fro=
m his winning position on Mango.=C2=A0Here is  the complaint, with a summar=
y of the trade:

The scheme worked as follows: EISENBERG used an account that he controlled =
on Mango Markets to sell a large amount of Perpetuals for MNGO and used a s=
eparate account on Mango Markets to purchase those same Perpetuals. In othe=
r words, EISENBERG sold himself MNGO Perpetuals. EISENBERG then engaged in =
a series of large purchases of MNGO, with the objective of artificially inc=
reasing the price of MNGO relative to USDC, which had the effect of increas=
ing the price of MNGO Perpetuals on Mango Markets. That purchasing achieved=
 the desired effect, causing the price of MNGO Perpetuals on Mango Markets =
to increase precipitously over the course of approximately 20 minutes. Over=
 that time span of approximately 20 minutes, the price of MNGO Perpetuals r=
ose from approximately 0.0382 USDC/MNGO to approximately 0.54 USDC/MANGO, a=
n increase of approximately 1300 percent.
As the price of MNGO Perpetuals on Mango Markets rose as a result of the Ma=
rket Manipulation Scheme perpetrated by AVRAHAM EISENBERG, the defendant, t=
he value of the MNGO Perpetuals that EISENBERG had purchased also rose. Bec=
ause Mango Markets allows investors to borrow and withdraw cryptocurrency b=
ased on the value of their assets on the platform, the increase in the valu=
e of the MNGO Perpetuals EISENBERG had purchased allowed EISENBERG to borro=
w, then withdraw, approximately $110 million worth of various cryptocurrenc=
ies from Mango Markets, which came from deposits of other investors in the =
Mango Markets exchange. When EISENBERG borrowed and withdrew that cryptocur=
rency, he had no intention to repay the borrowed funds. Accordingly, after =
EISENBERG borrowed and withdrew essentially all of the cryptocurrency depos=
its on the Mango Markets platform, EISENBERG ceased manipulating the price =
of MNGO Perpetuals, causing the price=C2=A0of MNGO Perpetuals to fall signi=
ficantly. Due to EISENBERG=E2=80=99s withdrawals, other investors with depo=
sits on Mango Markets lost much, or all, of those deposits.

Back in October, Eisenberg was quite proud of all this. Before doing the tr=
ade, he previewed it in some=C2=A0Discord posts,  describing it succinctly =
as =E2=80=9CYou take a long position. And then you make numba go up.=E2=80=
=9D After doing the trade, he tweeted a =E2=80=9C statement on recent event=
s=E2=80=9D that   I once wrote=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmight be up there with Satoshi=
 Nakamoto=E2=80=99s Bitcoin white paper as one of the great foundational do=
cuments of crypto=E2=80=9D:

I was involved with a team that operated a highly profitable trading strate=
gy last week.
I believe all of our actions were legal open market actions, using the prot=
ocol as designed, even if the development team did not fully anticipate all=
 the consequences of setting parameters the way they are.
Unfortunately, the exchange this took place on, Mango Markets, became insol=
vent as a result, with the insurance fund being insufficient to cover all l=
iquidations.

=E2=80=9CUsing the protocol as designed=E2=80=9D just meant that the code l=
et him do that, so he did. =E2=80=9CAll of our actions were legal open mark=
et actions=E2=80=9D apparently meant=C2=A0that he hadn=E2=80=99t been arres=
ted yet. Now he has been.
Last week   I wrote a postscript to =E2=80=9C  The Crypto Story=E2=80=9D fo=
r Bloomberg Businessweek. =E2=80=9COne imperfect but useful way to think ab=
out crypto,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cis that it allowed for the crea=
tion of a toy financial system.=E2=80=9D A lot of people in crypto=C2=A0des=
cribed=C2=A0it as a set of innovations that would have profound effects on =
the real world, on ordinary people=E2=80=99s daily lives. But a lot of peop=
le in the crypto=C2=A0financial system=C2=A0treated=C2=A0it as a game where=
 they could click some buttons on a computer and get rich with no real-worl=
d consequences. You are trading Mango tokens on Mango Markets! Doesn=E2=80=
=99t that sound fake? If you find a cool button to press to =E2=80=9Cmake n=
umba go up,=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t it seem like you could press it? Like =
it would just be fun and consequence-free?=C2=A0And yet the people who did =
that keep ending up in real jail.

