   =20
      Gemini vs. Genesis
   =20
 =20

At some level, if you were offering 8% interest rates on a crypto savings p=
roduct last year, you were involved in delusion. You were not paying 8% on =
crypto deposits because you were lending them out at 10% to homeowners who =
needed mortgages. Those crypto deposits were not funding real-world activit=
y that yielded 10% cash flows. Fundamentally, those crypto deposits   were =
part of a credit bubble, and they were used to fund various bets on=C2=A0th=
e continued growth of crypto markets. When the total value of crypto market=
s quadrupled in a year =E2=80=94=C2=A0 as it did in 2021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
n the people making those bets could very easily pay 10% interest to their =
lenders and still make a lot of money themselves, and everyone was happy. W=
hen the total value of crypto markets fell by two-thirds =E2=80=94=C2=A0as =
it has since its peak in 2021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the people making those b=
ets went bankrupt and their lenders lost money and froze withdrawals.
During the boom, nobody characterized things this way: Those 8% interest ra=
tes came from =E2=80=9Cyield farming=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Carbitrage=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Cstaking=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CDeFi liquidity provision=E2=80=
=9D or whatever. But now things are clearer, and fundamentally the yields=
=C2=A0came from bets on crypto going up.=C2=A0The advertising=C2=A0was basi=
cally that customers could get=C2=A0safe=C2=A08% yields on their crypto (or=
 stablecoin) deposits. The asterisk =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthese rates are=
 safe as long as crypto keeps growing, but if it contracts we=E2=80=99ll ha=
ve to shut down withdrawals and you might lose your money=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0was not quite spelled out.
Also there was a chain of delusion here: Some=C2=A0crypto lending platforms=
 offered 8% yields to retail customers and then took the money and bet it o=
n a bunch of random tokens going up, but most platforms had some intermedia=
te steps. You take deposits from retail customers, you lend them to an inst=
itutional lending firm, it lends them to a market-neutral arbitrage trading=
 firm, and the arbitrage trading firm turns out to just be betting=C2=A0on =
a bunch of random tokens going up. In that situation, if you are=C2=A0runni=
ng the retail platform, you have=C2=A0some deniability. =E2=80=9CI trusted =
my customers=E2=80=99 money to a stable institutional firm that promised me=
 safe returns; I can=E2=80=99t believe that=C2=A0they=C2=A0just invested it=
 in risky crypto bets!=E2=80=9D I mean! What did you think they were doing?=
 Why did=C2=A0you=C2=A0think those 8% yields were safe? Still, maybe you de=
luded yourself as well as your customers.
 Anyway:

The fallout from the collapse of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s crypto empire =
just got messier, with digital-asset entrepreneur Cameron Winklevoss accusi=
ng fellow businessman Barry Silbert of =E2=80=9Cbad faith stall tactics=E2=
=80=9D and the intermingling of funds within his conglomerate that Winklevo=
ss says have left $900 million in customer assets needlessly in limbo since=
 FTX=E2=80=99s meltdown.
Gemini Trust Co., founded by Winklevoss and his twin brother, paused redemp=
tions on a lending product called Earn, which offered investors the potenti=
al to generate as much as 8% in interest on their digital coins. It did so =
by lending them out to Genesis Global Capital, one of the companies owned b=
y Silbert=E2=80=99s Digital Currency Group.=C2=A0
The Earn halt came in November after Genesis suspended both redemptions and=
 new loan originations at its lending unit because of its exposure to FTX. =
Genesis has told clients that it could take =E2=80=9Cweeks=E2=80=9D to find=
 a path forward, and that bankruptcy may be one possibility.
Winklevoss, facing pressure of his own from angry customers locked out of t=
heir Gemini accounts and a lawsuit alleging fraud, in an open letter Monday=
 said he had provided Silbert with multiple proposals to resolve the issue,=
 including as recently as Dec. 25. He told Silbert =E2=80=9Cthis mess is en=
tirely of your own making,=E2=80=9D citing some $1.675 billion owed to Gene=
sis by DCG, which it used for other business purposes within Silbert=E2=80=
=99s conglomerate. =E2=80=9CThis is money that Genesis owes to Earn users a=
nd other creditors.=E2=80=9D

Here=E2=80=99s  the letter. =E2=80=9CStop trying to pretend that you and DC=
G are innocent bystanders and had nothing to do with creating this mess,=E2=
=80=9D Winklevoss also  tweeted at Silbert. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s completel=
y disingenuous.=E2=80=9D Yes! Well! And!

