   =20
      Should index funds be illegal?
   =20
 =20

A simple model that you could have for the stock market is that, as owning =
stocks becomes more convenient and pleasant, more people will buy stocks, a=
nd the prices of stocks will go up. In some ways this is an obvious and con=
ventional model: More people buy cars, refrigerators, etc. as it gets more =
convenient and pleasant to own those things. In other ways it is a weird an=
d contrarian model: Classic financial economics=C2=A0assumes that the only =
thing that matters about stocks is their cash flow, and it is sort of a cat=
egory error =E2=80=94=C2=A0or at least a matter for behavioral finance=C2=
=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0to talk about owning stocks being pleasant or unpleasant.=
 If a stock has high cash flows but is for some reason unpleasant to own, s=
ome people will sell it, but other people =E2=80=94=C2=A0arbitrageurs, hedg=
e funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0will look through the unpleasantness and buy it. Buy=
ing unpleasant cash flows =E2=80=94=C2=A0dealing with the administrative ha=
ssles or moral ambiguities or=C2=A0whatever that are required to take advan=
tage of lucrative complicated investing opportunities=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
s kind of the=C2=A0point=C2=A0of hedge funds, and hedge funds are big and n=
umerous and should be able to absorb a lot of unpleasantness.
Still I mean it is probably=C2=A0true=C2=A0that more people will buy stocks=
 as buying stocks becomes more convenient and pleasant? I suppose that is t=
he   basic idea of the   Boredom Markets Hypothesis: As owning stocks becam=
e relatively more entertaining during the pandemic (due to better stock-tra=
ding-as-entertainment technology, and due to much less competition from oth=
er entertainment options), a lot of stocks went up in ways that were perhap=
s not justified by expected future cash flows.=C2=A0
Also here=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CIndex Funds, Asset Prices and the Welfare of I=
nvestors,=E2=80=9D by Martin Schmalz and William Zame:
We present a general equilibrium model in which heterogeneous investors cho=
ose among bonds, stocks, and an Index Fund holding the market portfolio. We=
 show that, under standard assumptions, an equilibrium exists. We then deri=
ve predictions for equilibrium asset prices, investor behavior, and investo=
r welfare. The presence of the index fund (or a decrease in the fee charged=
 by the index fund) tends to increase stock market participation and thus i=
ncrease asset prices and decrease expected returns from investing in the st=
ock market. As a result, few - if any - investors benefit from the availabi=
lity of cheap market indexing.
The basic idea is:
=09An index fund is a good way to hold stocks: It has low fees and offers g=
ood diversification.=09Therefore, if there are index funds, more people wil=
l invest in the stock market (through the index funds) than if there were n=
o index funds.=09This will push up the price of stocks, pushing down their =
expected returns.=09Therefore the index funds are bad for investors.

From the paper:
The presence of the index Fund leads investors to shift wealth from bonds i=
nto stocks through the Fund in order to benefit from an increase in expecte=
d returns, and from individual stocks into the Fund in order to benefit fro=
m a decrease in risk. At the individual level, these shifts are welfare-imp=
roving. However, in the aggregate, these shifts increase the demand for sto=
ck, which in turn increases the price of stock. Because firm earnings remai=
n constant, expected returns fall.=C2=A0For reasonable ranges of parameters=
, we find that the welfare of many =E2=80=93 or even all =E2=80=93 investor=
s falls when the index Fund enters and continues to fall as the fee charged=
 by the Fund (the cost of iindexing) falls.
It is worth talking a little bit about the subtext here. Schmalz is a  lead=
ing proponent of   the idea that   increasing common ownership =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0where big index-y firms like BlackRock Inc. and Vanguard Group own large=
 stakes in lots of competing public companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0is bad for pro=
duct-market competition, because all of those public companies want to maxi=
mize the overall profits that they pay to their common owners instead of co=
mpeting for market share. If all the airlines have the same owners, then no=
 airline will want to cut prices to gain market share, because that would b=
e bad for its owners.
One standard objection to this theory that index funds hurt competition is =
=E2=80=9Cno they don=E2=80=99t,=E2=80=9D and there is mixed evidence for th=
at. But another popular objection is =E2=80=9Clook, even if widespread inde=
xing=C2=A0is=C2=A0a little bad for product-market competition, it is good f=
or investors, so we shouldn=E2=80=99t worry too much about it.=E2=80=9D Sch=
malz, here, is arguing that it is actually=C2=A0bad=C2=A0for investors, whi=
ch would make his worries about competition more compelling. If index funds=
 are bad, or at least a mixed bag, for investors, and they are bad for comp=
etition, then maybe that's worth doing something about.
Still it is a funny sort of objection. On this theory, index funds make it =
more pleasant to own stocks, which drives up the prices of stocks, which lo=
wers their expected returns, which is bad for investors. But it is also mor=
e pleasant! The investors are getting a benefit; they are just paying for i=
t.

