   =20
      Elsewhere in boredom
   =20
 =20

In the depths of the pandemic in 2020, a lot of people were stuck at home w=
ith nothing to do, so they started trading stocks. This made the pandemic l=
ess boring=C2=A0for them. But they also started=C2=A0talking=C2=A0a lot abo=
ut trading stocks, which made the pandemic much=C2=A0more=C2=A0boring=C2=A0=
for their loved ones. Here is  a funny Wall Street Journal story about a mu=
sician named Alan Garcia, who during the pandemic=C2=A0 stopped getting gig=
s and started trading stocks, but who has since gotten better:

The obsession didn=E2=80=99t end when he sat down in the living room with h=
is wife, Adriana Rodriguez, each evening. For about two years, he talked ab=
out investing. Mr. Garcia, a 34-year-old Houston resident, even started wat=
ching investing videos in bed at night.
=E2=80=9CHe was here,=E2=80=9D Ms. Rodriguez said, =E2=80=9Cbut he wasn=E2=
=80=99t here.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
In early 2022, Mr. Garcia lost everything in his portfolio on a bad options=
 bet, leaving him in a foul mood. But the next morning, he felt relieved. A=
fter Ms. Rodriguez, a lawyer, left for the office, he worked on his music a=
ll day instead of checking the market. He hasn=E2=80=99t traded on the app =
since.=C2=A0
Ms. Rodriguez is thrilled. Mr. Garcia agrees it is for the best=E2=80=94mos=
tly, anyway. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ve never been this good in our lives,=E2=
=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9COne day I=E2=80=99ll get that $2,000 back though.=
=E2=80=9D

A basic idea of the Boredom Markets Hypothesis is that trading stocks is ju=
st not intrinsically=C2=A0that=C2=A0fun. A society in which everyone is tra=
ding stocks for fun is a society where the opportunities for fun have sever=
ely atrophied. When your musician husband gets back to making music instead=
 of watching YouTube videos about options day-trading, that=E2=80=99s good =
for you and the world, even if it is bad for your bank account and the opti=
ons market.

