<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So here=E2=80=99s a trade.</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You open two accounts on a commodity =
futures exchange, Account A and Account B.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Using Account A, you offer to sell 10,000 tons of nickel futures a=
t a price of $30,000 per ton ($300 million total notional amount).</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Using Account B, you bid to buy 10,000=C2=
=A0tons of nickel futures at a price of=C2=A0$30,000 per ton.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Nobody else happens to be trading, so your orde=
rs cross with each other: Account B buys 10,000=C2=A0futures from Account A=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have to post some collateral=
 in each account, but it=E2=80=99s a fraction of the total notional amount.=
 Say it=E2=80=99s $30 million in Account A and $30 million in Account B, $6=
0 million total.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You also go aroun=
d to all the nickel producers and buy up all the nickel they=E2=80=99re pro=
ducing. Say you spend $130 million to buy all their nickel just to hoard it=
 for yourself.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">As a result, the pr=
ice of nickel doubles, to $60,000 per ton.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">Now Account B has $300 million of profits, though Account A has $3=
00 million of losses.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Using Accoun=
t B, you withdraw your $300 million of profits from the futures exchange an=
d bury it in your backyard.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Simult=
aneously, the futures exchange issues a margin call to Account A, asking it=
 for $300 million more collateral to cover its losses, but that call goes s=
traight to voicemail. Your account is in default, but you opened Account A =
under a fake name and they never get the money back from you.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Net, you have put in $190 million ($60 million =
of futures margin, $130 million to buy up a lot of physical nickel) and tak=
en out $300 million, for a $110 million profit.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is wrong with this trade? I think that th=
ere are three general=C2=A0classes<em>=C2=A0</em>of answer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One sort of answer is along the lines of: =E2=
=80=9CThis trade wouldn=E2=80=99t work.=E2=80=9D In fact, this trade wouldn=
=E2=80=99t work. Basically every step that I laid out above is superficiall=
y plausible, but the actual mechanics of nickel markets would prevent you f=
rom doing these things. Among other problems, you=E2=80=99d open your futur=
es accounts through brokers, who would do know-your-customer checks and get=
 your real name and phone number, so you couldn=E2=80=99t walk away from Ac=
count A. Also the exchange wouldn=E2=80=99t let you trade with yourself. Al=
so there would be a lot of other people trading on the exchange, so even if=
 the rules allowed you to trade with yourself, the odds of that happening w=
ould be low. Also you probably couldn=E2=80=99t push up the price of nickel=
 all that much by just spending $130 million: Nickel is abundant and useful=
 and so hard to corner; you would need to spend a ton of money relative to =
the amount you could make on the futures exchange.<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Also if you somehow did manage to double the price of nickel quic=
kly, the exchange might <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjItMTEtMzAvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1uaWNrZWwtbWFya2V0LWFs=
bW9zdC1icm9rZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTAzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV=
0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3=
R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf881534f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  shut down trading due =
to</a> =E2=80=9Cthe absence of rational market forces capable of explaining=
 these developments,=E2=80=9D so you couldn=E2=80=99t get your money out.=
=C2=A0The basic idea here is that nickel is a real thing with a real market=
, and you can=E2=80=99t just push it around to do this abstract manipulatio=
n. Other people will be doing stuff with nickel, and your elegant little ma=
nipulation will break down when it comes into contact with the real world.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another sort of answer would be: =E2=80=9CThis=
 trade is illegal.=E2=80=9D It is illegal because it is=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDQtMjYvd2hlbi1jbGV2ZXJuZXN=
zLWJlY29tZXMtbWFuaXB1bGF0aW9uP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZW=
RpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEwMyZ1dG1fY2Ftc=
GFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB14620afe" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">market man=
ipulation</a>, trading that is =E2=80=9Cspecifically intended to create or =
effect a price or price trend that does not reflect legitimate forces of su=
pply and demand.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0You have effectively stolen $300 million fro=
m the futures exchange with your uneconomic trading, and if you do this tra=
de in large enough size you might bankrupt the exchange and=C2=A0cause its =
other customers to lose money. Other people are counting on the nickel exch=
ange to work in a sensible and economically rational way, and you are treat=
ing it as a dumb game. This is bad for the other users of the futures marke=
t, and so it is properly illegal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third sort of answer would be: =E2=80=9CThis=
 trade is bad for the world.=E2=80=9D It is bad <em>in part=C2=A0</em>becau=
se it is market manipulation, stealing from other exchange users, but that=
=E2=80=99s not the only reason. Nickel is a real thing that real people use=
 in real-world applications, and your dumb manipulation requires you to cor=
ner the market and push up prices. People can=E2=80=99t make batteries=C2=
=A0or bathroom fixtures because you are doing financial shenanigans. Even i=
f the exchange and its other customers didn=E2=80=99t care =E2=80=94=C2=A0e=
ven if everyone trading nickel futures thought =E2=80=9Cwe are playing a du=
mb game and sometimes we will lose to smarter players=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0this would still be bad, because the nickel market has ramifications in =
the real world.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But let us change the facts slightly. Instead =
of nickel, let=E2=80=99s do this trade in crypto, on a decentralized financ=
e exchange, and let=E2=80=99s trade the exchange=E2=80=99s own crypto token=
. We=E2=80=99ll go on Mango Markets, a DeFi trading platform, and trade fut=
ures on Mango=E2=80=99s own MNGO token. Here we can, sort of, solve all of =
these objections:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The market might be constructed poorl=
y enough that you could actually get away with doing this. It might let you=
 open accounts without any know-your-customer checks or any recourse to you=
, it might let you withdraw money instantly against irrational price moves,=
 it might be illiquid enough that you could trade with yourself and push up=
 prices dramatically without spending much money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CEhh it=E2=80=99s on the blockchain, decentralized =
finance, no laws apply,=E2=80=9D you might say to yourself. Not legal advic=
e! We will come back to this one!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
Absolutely no one makes any real-world use of MNGO tokens whatsoever; nobod=
y is deprived of batteries or bathroom fixtures because you briefly cornere=
d some token market.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t want to endorse these argument=
s, but one could. You might say: Look, trading MNGO tokens absolutely=C2=A0=
<em>is</em>, only, a dumb game. It has no consequences in the real world, a=
nd also no constraints=C2=A0<em>from=C2=A0</em>the real world. Mango=E2=80=
=99s own rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0the code that determines how you set up an ac=
count on Mango, how you trade futures, how much money you can take out, etc=
. =E2=80=94=C2=A0are the only rules that apply to this game, and if those r=
ules allow you to do this thing then you can do it. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s=
 market manipulation,=E2=80=9D someone might object, but you will reply tha=
t that is an irrelevancy, a false analogy to other markets. <em>This </em>m=
arket is just a game, and the rules of this game are just what is encoded i=
n the market=E2=80=99s protocols; =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulation=E2=80=9D is =
a concept that comes from different markets with other economic=C2=A0purpos=
es. Cornering the nickel market is bad, for people who need nickel for thei=
r kitchens; cornering the MNGO market is morally and economically neutral.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One problem with this line of thinking is that=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s still market manipulation? Like, if you do thi=
s, then Mango and its other customers=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>lose money, a=
nd you will be taking it from them, and they will feel aggrieved. Many of t=
he reasons that market manipulation is bad in the real world =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it feels unfair, it undermines confidence in markets, it takes advantage=
 of smaller less sophisticated traders =E2=80=94=C2=A0also apply here.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another problem with this line of thinking is =
that, if you=C2=A0<em>like=C2=A0</em>decentralized finance, if you think it=
 has the potential to build a good alternative financial system, then this =
attitude =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthis is all a dumb game with no outside ru=
les, and you win the game by tricking everyone else=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0seems bad. Hard to build the financial system of the future on that basi=
s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third problem with this line of thinking is =
that federal prosecutors disagree! They are definitely going to think it=E2=
=80=99s market manipulation, and they=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMjgvY3J5cHRvLXRyYWRlci1jaGFyZ2VkLXdpdGgtZnJhd=
WQtaW4tMTEwLW1pbGxpb24tYWxsZWdlZC1tYW5nby1tYXJrZXRzLXNjYW0_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEw=
MzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjMwMTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
1c2c8bdd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  will try to put you in jail</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A cryptocurrency trader accused of rigging the=
 Mango Markets exchange and attempting to steal $110 million was arrested i=
n Puerto Rico and charged with fraud by prosecutors in New York.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Avraham Eisenberg allegedly used two Mango Mar=
kets accounts he controlled to manipulate the price of Mango perpetual swap=
s, which are futures that allow traders to keep positions open. All he need=
ed was 20 minutes to push up the price of the swaps by 1,300%, according to=
 a criminal complaint unsealed [last] Tuesday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eisenberg used his swaps, which had increased =
in value, to borrow, then withdraw, about $110 million worth of various cry=
ptocurrencies which came from the deposits of other investors on the exchan=
ge, according to the complaint.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDue to Eisenberg=E2=80=99s withdrawal=
s, other investors with deposits on Mango Markets lost much, or all, of tho=
se deposits,=E2=80=9D the complaint says.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eisenberg later agreed to return $67 million t=
o Mango, according to the complaint.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked about this trade <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTIvZGVmaS1kaXNjb3ZlcnMtbmV3=
LW1hcmtldC1tYW5pcHVsYXRpb25zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEwMyZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB70e92237" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  back in O=
ctober</a>, and it is schematically what I laid out above: Eisenberg sold h=
imself a huge quantity of perpetual MNGO futures in the thin Mango futures =
market, bought a bunch of MNGO in the spot market to manipulate the price u=
p, and then withdrew a bunch of money from his winning position on Mango.=
=C2=A0Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3014=
3722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmR=
meElVL3JPWHlfUDdVNEhTVS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0954e259" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the=
 complaint</a>, with a summary of the trade:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The scheme worked as follows: EISENBERG used a=
n account that he controlled on Mango Markets to sell a large amount of Per=
petuals for MNGO and used a separate account on Mango Markets to purchase t=
hose same Perpetuals. In other words, EISENBERG sold himself MNGO Perpetual=
s. EISENBERG then engaged in a series of large purchases of MNGO, with the =
objective of artificially increasing the price of MNGO relative to USDC, wh=
ich had the effect of increasing the price of MNGO Perpetuals on Mango Mark=
ets. That purchasing achieved the desired effect, causing the price of MNGO=
 Perpetuals on Mango Markets to increase precipitously over the course of a=
pproximately 20 minutes. Over that time span of approximately 20 minutes, t=
he price of MNGO Perpetuals rose from approximately 0.0382 USDC/MNGO to app=
roximately 0.54 USDC/MANGO, an increase of approximately 1300 percent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the price of MNGO Perpetuals on Mango Marke=
ts rose as a result of the Market Manipulation Scheme perpetrated by AVRAHA=
M EISENBERG, the defendant, the value of the MNGO Perpetuals that EISENBERG=
 had purchased also rose. Because Mango Markets allows investors to borrow =
and withdraw cryptocurrency based on the value of their assets on the platf=
orm, the increase in the value of the MNGO Perpetuals EISENBERG had purchas=
ed allowed EISENBERG to borrow, then withdraw, approximately $110 million w=
orth of various cryptocurrencies from Mango Markets, which came from deposi=
ts of other investors in the Mango Markets exchange. When EISENBERG borrowe=
d and withdrew that cryptocurrency, he had no intention to repay the borrow=
ed funds. Accordingly, after EISENBERG borrowed and withdrew essentially al=
l of the cryptocurrency deposits on the Mango Markets platform, EISENBERG c=
eased manipulating the price of MNGO Perpetuals, causing the price=C2=A0of =
MNGO Perpetuals to fall significantly. Due to EISENBERG=E2=80=99s withdrawa=
ls, other investors with deposits on Mango Markets lost much, or all, of th=
ose deposits.</p>
</blockquote>
