<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some level, if you were offering 8% interes=
t rates on a crypto savings product last year, you were involved in delusio=
n. You were not paying 8% on crypto deposits because you were lending them =
out at 10% to homeowners who needed mortgages. Those crypto deposits were n=
ot funding real-world activity that yielded 10% cash flows. Fundamentally, =
those crypto deposits <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjItMTItMDUvY3J5cHRvLWhhZC1hLWNyZWRpdC1idWJibGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEwMzIzX0=
1PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlc=
m09MjMwMTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB263c39=
74" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  were part of a credit bubble</a>, and they were used to fund=
 various bets on=C2=A0<em>the continued growth of crypto markets</em>. When=
 the total value of crypto markets quadrupled in a year =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cH=
M6Ly9jb2lubWFya2V0Y2FwLmNvbS9jaGFydHMv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB38fc3dd7" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> as it did in 2021</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the people making those b=
ets could very easily pay 10% interest to their lenders and still make a lo=
t of money themselves, and everyone was happy. When the total value of cryp=
to markets fell by two-thirds =E2=80=94=C2=A0as it has since its peak in 20=
21 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the people making those bets went bankrupt and their=
 lenders lost money and froze withdrawals.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the boom, nobody characterized things t=
his way: Those 8% interest rates came from =E2=80=9Cyield farming=E2=80=9D =
or =E2=80=9Carbitrage=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cstaking=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CDeF=
i liquidity provision=E2=80=9D or whatever. But now things are clearer, and=
 fundamentally the yields=C2=A0came from bets on crypto going up.=C2=A0The =
advertising=C2=A0was basically that customers could get=C2=A0<em>safe=C2=A0=
</em>8% yields on their crypto (or stablecoin) deposits. The asterisk =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthese rates are safe as long as crypto keeps growing, =
but if it contracts we=E2=80=99ll have to shut down withdrawals and you mig=
ht lose your money=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0was not quite spelled out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also there was a chain of delusion here: <em>S=
ome=C2=A0</em>crypto lending platforms offered 8% yields to retail customer=
s and then took the money and bet it on a bunch of random tokens going up, =
but most platforms had some intermediate steps. You take deposits from reta=
il customers, you lend them to an institutional lending firm, it lends them=
 to a market-neutral arbitrage trading firm, and the arbitrage trading firm=
 turns out to just be betting=C2=A0on a bunch of random tokens going up. In=
 that situation, if you are=C2=A0running the retail platform, you have=C2=
=A0some deniability. =E2=80=9CI trusted my customers=E2=80=99 money to a st=
able institutional firm that promised me safe returns; I can=E2=80=99t beli=
eve that=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>just invested it in risky crypto bets!=E2=
=80=9D I mean! What did you think they were doing? Why did=C2=A0<em>you=C2=
=A0</em>think those 8% yields were safe? Still, maybe you deluded yourself =
as well as your customers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMDIvZ2VtaW5pLXMtY2FtZXJvbi13aW5rbGV2b3NzLWFjY3VzZXMtZGNnLWN=
lby1iYXJyeS1zaWxiZXJ0LW9mLWJhZC1mYWl0aC10YWN0aWNzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDMyM19NT0=
5FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtP=
TIzMDEwMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB82ef537e=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> Anyway</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fallout from the collapse of Sam Bankman-F=
ried=E2=80=99s crypto empire just got messier, with digital-asset entrepren=
eur Cameron Winklevoss accusing fellow businessman Barry Silbert of =E2=80=
=9Cbad faith stall tactics=E2=80=9D and the intermingling of funds within h=
is conglomerate that Winklevoss says have left $900 million in customer ass=
ets needlessly in limbo since FTX=E2=80=99s meltdown.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gemini Trust Co., founded by Winklevoss and hi=
s twin brother, paused redemptions on a lending product called Earn, which =
offered investors the potential to generate as much as 8% in interest on th=
eir digital coins. It did so by lending them out to Genesis Global Capital,=
 one of the companies owned by Silbert=E2=80=99s Digital Currency Group.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Earn halt came in November after Genesis s=
uspended both redemptions and new loan originations at its lending unit bec=
ause of its exposure to FTX. Genesis has told clients that it could take =
=E2=80=9Cweeks=E2=80=9D to find a path forward, and that bankruptcy may be =
one possibility.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Winklevoss, facing pressure of his own from an=
gry customers locked out of their Gemini accounts and a lawsuit alleging fr=
aud, in an open letter Monday said he had provided Silbert with multiple pr=
oposals to resolve the issue, including as recently as Dec. 25. He told Sil=
bert =E2=80=9Cthis mess is entirely of your own making,=E2=80=9D citing som=
e $1.675 billion owed to Genesis by DCG, which it used for other business p=
urposes within Silbert=E2=80=99s conglomerate. =E2=80=9CThis is money that =
Genesis owes to Earn users and other creditors.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
