<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A simple model that you could have for the sto=
ck market is that, as owning stocks becomes more convenient and pleasant, m=
ore people will buy stocks, and the prices of stocks will go up. In some wa=
ys this is an obvious and conventional model: More people buy cars, refrige=
rators, etc. as it gets more convenient and pleasant to own those things. I=
n other ways it is a weird and contrarian model: Classic <em>financial</em>=
 economics=C2=A0assumes that the only thing that matters about stocks is th=
eir cash flow, and it is sort of a category error =E2=80=94=C2=A0or at leas=
t a matter for behavioral finance=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0to talk about owning =
stocks being pleasant or unpleasant. If a stock has high cash flows but is =
for some reason unpleasant to own, some people will sell it, but other peop=
le =E2=80=94=C2=A0arbitrageurs, hedge funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0will look throug=
h the unpleasantness and buy it. Buying unpleasant cash flows =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0dealing with the administrative hassles or moral ambiguities or=C2=A0wha=
tever that are required to take advantage of lucrative complicated investin=
g opportunities=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0is kind of the=C2=A0<em>point=C2=A0</em=
>of hedge funds, and hedge funds are big and numerous and should be able to=
 absorb a lot of unpleasantness.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still I mean it is probably=C2=A0<em>true=C2=
=A0</em>that more people will buy stocks as buying stocks becomes more conv=
enient and pleasant? I suppose that is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDQtMzAvaWYteW91LXJlLWJvcmVkLXlvdS1jYW4tdHJhZ=
GUtc3RvY2tzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDMyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRt=
X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEwMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
mZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB616548b5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  basic idea</a> of the <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMDkvdGhlLWJhZ=
C1zdG9ja3MtYXJlLXRoZS1tb3N0LWZ1bj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTAzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1f=
bWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMDMmdXRtX2N=
hbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe775e0e2" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bored=
om Markets Hypothesis</a>: As owning stocks became relatively more entertai=
ning during the pandemic (due to better stock-trading-as-entertainment tech=
nology, and due to much less competition from other entertainment options),=
 a lot of stocks went up in ways that were perhaps not justified by expecte=
d future cash flows.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also here=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnM=
uc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQyNDYzMjE/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cB6e3842d3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Index Funds, Asset Prices and the Welfare of =
Investors</a>,=E2=80=9D by Martin Schmalz and William Zame:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We present a general equilibrium m=
odel in which heterogeneous investors choose among bonds, stocks, and an In=
dex Fund holding the market portfolio. We show that, under standard assumpt=
ions, an equilibrium exists. We then derive predictions for equilibrium ass=
et prices, investor behavior, and investor welfare. The presence of the ind=
ex fund (or a decrease in the fee charged by the index fund) tends to incre=
ase stock market participation and thus increase asset prices and decrease =
expected returns from investing in the stock market. As a result, few - if =
any - investors benefit from the availability of cheap market indexing.</p>=
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic idea is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">An index fund is a good way to hold s=
tocks: It has low fees and offers good diversification.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore, if there are index funds, more people will=
 invest in the stock market (through the index funds) than if there were no=
 index funds.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This will push up th=
e price of stocks, pushing down their expected returns.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore the index funds are bad for investors.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From the paper:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The presence of the index Fund lea=
ds investors to shift wealth from bonds into stocks through the Fund in ord=
er to benefit from an increase in expected returns, and from individual sto=
cks into the Fund in order to benefit from a decrease in risk. At the indiv=
idual level, these shifts are welfare-improving. However, in the aggregate,=
 these shifts increase the demand for stock, which in turn increases the pr=
ice of stock. Because firm earnings remain constant, expected returns fall.=
=C2=A0For reasonable ranges of parameters, we find that the welfare of many=
 =E2=80=93 or even all =E2=80=93 investors falls when the index Fund enters=
 and continues to fall as the fee charged by the Fund (the cost of iindexin=
g) falls.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is worth talking a little bit about the sub=
text here. Schmalz is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP=
2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTI0MjczNDU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC57f0615b" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> lead=
ing proponent</a> of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMTgtMTItMDcvcmVndWxhdG9ycy1hc2staWYtaW5kZXgtZnVuZHMtYXJlLWJhZD9jbXBpZD1=
CQkQwMTAzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldH=
RlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBd843e667" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  the idea</a> that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/30143722.279526/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDQtMTYvc2hvdWxkLW11dHVhbC1mdW5kcy1iZS1pbG=
xlZ2FsLT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTAzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb=
3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB076622e3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  increasing common ownership</a=
> =E2=80=94=C2=A0where big index-y firms like BlackRock Inc. and Vanguard G=
roup own large stakes in lots of competing public companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
is bad for product-market competition, because all of those public companie=
s want to maximize the overall profits that they pay to their common owners=
 instead of competing for market share. If all the airlines have the same o=
wners, then no airline will want to cut prices to gain market share, becaus=
e that would be bad for its owners.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One standard objection to this theory that ind=
ex funds hurt competition is =E2=80=9Cno they don=E2=80=99t,=E2=80=9D and t=
here is mixed evidence for that. But another popular objection is =E2=80=9C=
look, even if widespread indexing=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>a little bad for pr=
oduct-market competition, it is good for investors, so we shouldn=E2=80=99t=
 worry too much about it.=E2=80=9D Schmalz, here, is arguing that it is act=
ually=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>for investors, which would make his worries ab=
out competition more compelling. If index funds are bad, or at least a mixe=
d bag, for investors, and they are bad for competition, then maybe that's w=
orth doing something about.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still it is a funny sort of objection. On this=
 theory, index funds make it more pleasant to own stocks, which drives up t=
he prices of stocks, which lowers their expected returns, which is bad for =
investors. But it is also more pleasant! The investors are getting a benefi=
t; they are just paying for it.</p>
